# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: k-anonymity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The de-identification process involves masking, generalizing or deleting both direct and indirect identifiers; the definition of this process is not universal.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Information in the public domain, even seemingly anonymized, may thus be re-identified in combination with other pieces of available data and basic computer science techniques.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The Protection of Human Subjects ('Common Rule'), a collection of multiple U.S. federal agencies and departments including the U.S.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Department of Health and Human Services, warn that re-identification is becoming gradually easier because of "big data"—the abundance and constant collection and analysis of information along with the evolution of technologies and the advances of algorithms.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] However, others have claimed that de-identification is a safe and effective data liberation tool and do not view re-identification as a concern.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] More and more data are becoming publicly available over the Internet.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] These data are released after applying some anonymization techniques like removing personally identifiable information (PII) such as names, addresses and social security numbers to ensure the sources' privacy.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] This assurance of privacy allows the government to legally share limited data sets with third parties without requiring written permission.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Such data has proved to be very valuable for researchers, particularly in health care.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] GDPR-compliant pseudonymization seeks to reduce the risk of re-identification through the use of separately kept "additional information".
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The approach is based on an expert evaluation of a dataset to designate some identifiers as "direct" and some as "indirect." Proponents of this approach argue that re-identification can be avoided by limiting access to "additional information" that is kept separately by the controller.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The theory is that access to separately kept "additional information" is required for re-identification, attribution of data to a specific data subject can be limited by the controller to support lawful purposes only.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] This approach is controversial, as it fails if there are additional datasets that can be used for re-identification.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Such additional datasets may be unknown to those certifying the GDPR-compliant pseudonymization, or may not at exist at the time of the pseudonymization but may come into existence at some point in the future.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Existing privacy regulations typically protect information that has been modified, so that the data is deemed anonymized, or de-identified.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] For financial information, the Federal Trade Commission permits its circulation if it is de-identified and aggregated.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] In terms of university records, authorities both on the state and federal level have shown an awareness about issues of privacy in education and a distaste for institutions' disclosure of information.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Medical information of patients are becoming increasingly available on the Internet, on free and publicly accessing platforms such as HealthData.gov and PatientsLikeMe, encouraged by government open data policies and data sharing initiatives spearheaded by the private sector.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] While this level of accessibility yields many benefits, concerns regarding discrimination and privacy have been raised.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Protections on medical records and consumer data from pharmacies are stronger compared to those for other kinds of consumer data.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) protects the privacy of identifiable data about health, but authorize information release to third parties if de-identified.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] In addition, it mandates that patients receive breach notifications should there be more than a low probability that the patient's information was inappropriately disclosed or utilized without sufficient mitigation of the harm to him or her.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The likelihood of re-identification is a factor in determining the probability that the patient's information has been compromised.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Commonly, pharmacies sell de-identified information to data mining companies that sell to pharmaceutical companies in turn.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] There have been state laws enacted to ban data mining of medical information, but they were struck down by federal courts in Maine and New Hampshire on First Amendment grounds.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Another federal court on another case used "illusive" to describe concerns about privacy of patients and did not recognize the risks of re-identification.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The Notice of Proposed Rule Making, published by the Common Rule Agencies in September 2015, expanded the umbrella term of "human subject" in research to include biospecimens, or materials taken from the human body - blood, urine, tissue etc.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] This mandates that researchers using biospecimens must follow the stricter requirements of doing research with human subjects.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The rationale for this is the increased risk of re-identification of biospecimen.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The final revisions affirmed this regulation.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] There have been a sizable amount of successful attempts of re-identification in different fields.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Even if it is not easy for a lay person to break anonymity, once the steps to do so are disclosed and learnt, there is no need for higher level knowledge to access information in a database.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Sometimes, technical expertise is not even needed if a population has a unique combination of identifiers.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] In the mid-1990s, a government agency in Massachusetts called Group Insurance Commission (GIC), which purchased health insurance for employees of the state, decided to release records of hospital visits to any researcher who requested the data, at no cost.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] GIC assured that the patient's privacy was not a concern since it had removed identifiers such as name, addresses, social security numbers.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] However, information such as zip codes, birth date and sex remained untouched.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The GIC assurance was reinforced by the then governor of Massachusetts, William Weld.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Latanya Sweeney, a graduate student at the time, put her mind to picking out the governor's records in the GIC data.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] By combining the GIC data with the voter database of the city Cambridge, which she purchased for 20 dollars, Governor Weld's record was discovered with ease.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] In 1997, a researcher successfully de-anonymized medical records using voter databases.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] In 2011, Professor Latanya Sweeney again used anonymized hospital visit records and voting records in the state of Washington and successfully matched individual persons 43% of the time.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] There are existing algorithms used to re-identify patient with prescription drug information.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Two researchers at the University of Texas, Arvind Narayanan and Professor Vitaly Shmatikov, were able to re-identify some portion of anonymized Netflix movie-ranking data with individual consumers on the streaming website.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The data was released by Netflix 2006 after de-identification, which consisted of replacing individual names with random numbers and moving around personal details.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The two researchers de-anonymized some of the data by comparing it with non-anonymous IMDb (Internet Movie Database) users' movie ratings.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Very little information from the database, it was found, was needed to identify the subscriber.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] In the resulting research paper, there were startling revelations of how easy it is to re-identify Netflix users.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] For example, simply knowing data about only two movies a user has reviewed, including the precise rating and the date of rating give or take three days allows for 68% re-identification success.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] In 2006, after AOL published its users' search queries, data that was anonymized prior to the public release, *The New York Times* reporters successfully carried out re-identification of individuals by taking groups of searches made by anonymized users.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] AOL had attempted to suppress identifying information, including usernames and IP addresses, but had replaced these with unique identification numbers to preserve the utility of this data for researchers.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Arnold acknowledged that she was the author of the searches, confirming that re-identification is possible.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Location data - series of geographical positions in time that describe a person's whereabouts and movements - is a class of personal data that is specifically hard to keep anonymous.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Location shows recurring visits to frequently attended places of everyday life such as home, workplace, shopping, healthcare or specific spare-time patterns.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Only removing a person's identity from location data will not remove identifiable patterns such as commuting rhythms, sleeping places, or work places.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] By mapping coordinates onto addresses, location data is easily re-identified or correlated with a person's private life contexts.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Streams of location information play an important role in the reconstruction of personal identifiers from smartphone data accessed by apps.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] In 2019, Professor Kerstin Noëlle Vokinger and Dr.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] In general, involved private parties (such as pharmaceutical companies) and information that would reveal the private party (for example, drug names) are anonymized in Swiss judgments.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The researchers were able to re-identify 84% of the relevant anonymized cases of the Federal Supreme Court of Switzerland by linking information from publicly accessible databases.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] This achievement was covered by the media and started a debate if and how court cases should be anonymized.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] In 1997, Latanya Sweeney found from a study of Census records that up to 87 percent of the U.S. population can be identified using a combination of their 5-digit zip code, gender, and date of birth.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Unauthorized re-identification on the basis of such combinations does not require access to separately kept "additional information" that is under the control of the data controller, as is now required for GDPR-compliant pseudonymization.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Individuals whose data is re-identified are also at risk of having their information, with their identity attached to it, sold to organizations they do not want possessing private information about their finances, health or preferences.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] The release of this data may cause anxiety, shame or embarrassment.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] Once an individual's privacy has been breached as a result of re-identification, future breaches become much easier: once a link is made between one piece of data and a person's real identity, any association between the data and an anonymous identity breaks the anonymity of the person.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] While a complete ban on re-identification has been urged, enforcement would be difficult.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] A small-scale re-identification ban may also be imposed on trusted recipients of particular databases, such as government data miners or researchers.
[src:k-anonymity/data-re-identification] This ban would be much easier to enforce and may discourage re-identification.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] Identifiers such as names are suppressed, non-identifying values are allowed to remain, and the quasi-identifiers need to be processed so that every distinct combination of quasi-identifiers designates at least *k* records.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] The example table below presents a fictional, non-anonymized database consisting of the patient records for a fictitious hospital.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] The *Name* column is an identifier, *Age*, *Gender*, *State of domicile*, and *Religion* are quasi-identifiers, and *Disease* is a non-identifying sensitive value.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] Are they also non-identifying sensitive values, or are they quasi-identifiers?
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] There are 6 attributes and 10 records in this data.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] In this method, individual values of attributes are replaced with a broader category.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] For example, the value "19" of the attribute *Age* may be replaced by "≤ 20", the value "23" by "20 < Age ≤ 30", etc.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] The next table shows the anonymized database.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] This data has 2-anonymity with respect to the attributes *Age*, *Gender* and *State of domicile*, since for any combination of these attributes found in any row of the table there are always at least 2 rows with those exact attributes.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] The attributes available to an adversary are called quasi-identifiers.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] Each quasi-identifier tuple occurs in at least *k* records for a dataset with *k*-anonymity.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] The following example demonstrates a failing with *k*-anonymity: there may exist other data records that can be linked on the variables that are allegedly non-identifying.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] For instance, suppose an attacker is able to obtain the log from the person who was taking vital signs as part of the study and learns that Kishor was at the hospital on April 30 and is 180 cm tall.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] This information can be used to link with the "anonymized" database (which may have been published on the Internet) and learn that Kishor has a heart-related disease.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] An attacker who knows that Kishor visited the hospital on April 30 may be able to infer this simply knowing that Kishor is 180 cm height, roughly 80–82 kg, and comes from Karnataka.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] The root of this problem is the core problem with *k*-anonymity: there is no way to mathematically, unambiguously determine whether an attribute is an identifier, a quasi-identifier, or a non-identifying sensitive value.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] In fact, all values are potentially identifying, depending on their prevalence in the population and on auxiliary data that the attacker may have.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] Other privacy mechanisms such as differential privacy do not share this problem.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] Although k-anonymity safeguards against identity revelations, it does not shield against the disclosure of specific attributes.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] This becomes problematic when attackers possess background knowledge.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] Additionally, the absence of diversity in sensitive domains may result in the exposure of personal information.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] In such scenarios, opting for ℓ-Diversity might offer a more robust privacy safeguard.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] Meyerson and Williams (2004) demonstrated that optimal *k*-anonymity is an NP-hard problem, however heuristic methods such as *k*-Optimize as given by Bayardo and Agrawal (2005) often yield effective results.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] A practical approximation algorithm that enables solving the *k*-anonymization problem with an approximation guarantee of $O(\log k)$ was presented by Kenig and Tassa.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] While *k*-anonymity is a relatively simple-to-implement approach for de-identifying a dataset prior to public release, it is susceptible to many attacks.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] When background knowledge is available to an attacker, such attacks become even more effective.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] Because *k*-anonymization does not include any randomization, attackers can make reliable, unambiguous inferences about data sets that may harm individuals.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] For example, if the 19-year-old John from Kerala is known to be in the database above, then it can be reliably said that he has either cancer, a heart-related disease, or a viral infection.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] It has also been shown that *k*-anonymity can skew the results of a data set if it disproportionately suppresses and generalizes data points with unrepresentative characteristics.
[src:k-anonymity/k-anonymity] The suppression and generalization algorithms used to *k*-anonymize datasets can be altered, however, so that they do not have such a skewing effect.
[src:k-anonymity/l-diversity] While *k*-anonymity is a promising approach to take for group based anonymization given its simplicity and wide array of algorithms that perform it, it is however susceptible to many attacks.
[src:k-anonymity/l-diversity] Given the existence of such attacks where sensitive attributes may be inferred for *k*-anonymity data, the *l*-diversity method was created to further *k*-anonymity by additionally maintaining the diversity of sensitive fields.
[src:k-anonymity/l-diversity] A table has entropy *l*-diversity when for every equivalent class *E*, *Entropy*(*E*) ≥ log(*l*).
[src:k-anonymity/l-diversity] **Recursive (*c*-*l*)-diversity** – A compromise definition that ensures the most common value does not appear too often while less common values are ensured to not appear too infrequently.
[src:k-anonymity/l-diversity] Aggarwal and Yu (2008) note that when there is more than one sensitive field the *l*-diversity problem becomes more difficult due to added dimensionalities.
[src:k-anonymity/quasi-identifier] Quasi-identifiers can thus, when combined, become personally identifying information.
[src:k-anonymity/quasi-identifier] This process is called re-identification.
[src:k-anonymity/quasi-identifier] As an example, Latanya Sweeney has shown that even though neither gender, birth dates nor postal codes uniquely identify an individual, the combination of all three is sufficient to identify 87% of individuals in the United States.
[src:k-anonymity/quasi-identifier] The term was introduced by Tore Dalenius in 1986.
[src:k-anonymity/quasi-identifier] Since then, quasi-identifiers have been the basis of several attacks on released data.
[src:k-anonymity/quasi-identifier] For instance, Sweeney linked health records to publicly available information to locate the then-governor of Massachusetts' hospital records using uniquely identifying quasi-identifiers, and Sweeney, Abu and Winn used public voter records to re-identify participants in the Personal Genome Project.
[src:k-anonymity/quasi-identifier] Additionally, Arvind Narayanan and Vitaly Shmatikov discussed on quasi-identifiers to indicate statistical conditions for de-anonymizing data released by Netflix.
[src:k-anonymity/quasi-identifier] Motwani and Ying warn about potential privacy breaches being enabled by publication of large volumes of government and business data containing quasi-identifiers.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] "Record linkage" is the term used by statisticians, epidemiologists, and historians, among others, to describe the process of joining records from one data source with another that describe the same entity.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] However, many other terms are used for this process.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Unfortunately, this profusion of terminology has led to few cross-references between these research communities.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Computer scientists often refer to it as "data matching" or as the "object identity problem".
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Commercial mail and database applications refer to it as "merge/purge processing" or "list washing".
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] While they share similar names, record linkage and linked data are two separate approaches to processing and structuring data.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] The initial idea of record linkage goes back to Halbert L.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Dunn in his 1946 article titled "Record Linkage" published in the *American Journal of Public Health*.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Howard Borden Newcombe then laid the probabilistic foundations of modern record linkage theory in a 1959 article in *Science*.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] These were formalized in 1969 by Ivan Fellegi and Alan Sunter, in their pioneering work "A Theory For Record Linkage", where they proved that the probabilistic decision rule they described was optimal when the comparison attributes were conditionally independent.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] In their work they recognized the growing interest in applying advances in computing and automation to large collections of administrative data, and the *Fellegi-Sunter theory* remains the mathematical foundation for many record linkage applications.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Since the late 1990s, various machine learning techniques have been developed that can, under favorable conditions, be used to estimate the conditional probabilities required by the Fellegi-Sunter theory.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] On the other hand, machine learning or neural network algorithms that do not rely on these assumptions often provide far higher accuracy, when sufficient labeled training data is available.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Record linkage can be done entirely without the aid of a computer, but the primary reasons computers are often used to complete record linkages are to reduce or eliminate manual review and to make results more easily reproducible.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Computer matching has the advantages of allowing central supervision of processing, better quality control, speed, consistency, and better reproducibility of results.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Record linkage is highly sensitive to the quality of the data being linked, so all data sets under consideration (particularly their key identifier fields) should ideally undergo a data quality assessment before record linkage.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Many key identifiers for the same entity can be presented quite differently between (and even within) data sets, which can greatly complicate record linkage unless understood ahead of time.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] For example, key identifiers for a man named William J.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] In this example, the different formatting styles lead to records that look different but in fact all refer to the same entity with the same logical identifier values.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Most, if not all, record linkage strategies would result in more accurate linkage if these values were first *normalized* or *standardized* into a consistent format (e.g., all names are "Surname, Given name", and all dates are "YYYY/MM/DD").
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Standardization can be accomplished through simple rule-based data transformations or more complex procedures such as lexicon-based tokenization and probabilistic hidden Markov models.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Several of the packages listed in the *Software Implementations* section provide some of these features to simplify the process of data standardization.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Entity resolution engines are typically used to uncover risk, fraud, and conflicts of interest, but are also useful tools for use within customer data integration (CDI) and master data management (MDM) requirements.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Typical uses for entity resolution engines include terrorist screening, insurance fraud detection, USA Patriot Act compliance, organized retail crime ring detection and applicant screening.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] For example, across different data silos – employee records, vendor data, watch lists, etc. – an organization may have several variations of an entity named ABC, which may or may not be the same individual.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] These entries may, in fact, appear as ABC1, ABC2, or ABC3 within those data sources.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] By comparing similarities between underlying attributes such as address, date of birth, or social security number, the user can eliminate some possible matches and confirm others as very likely matches.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Entity resolution engines then apply rules, based on common sense logic, to identify hidden relationships across the data.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] In the example above, perhaps ABC1 and ABC2 are not the same individual, but rather two distinct people who share common attributes such as address or phone number.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] While entity resolution solutions include data matching technology, many data matching offerings do not fit the definition of entity resolution.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] In contrast to data quality products, more powerful identity resolution engines also include a rules engine and workflow process, which apply business intelligence to the resolved identities and their relationships.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] These advanced technologies make automated decisions and impact business processes in real time, limiting the need for human intervention.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] The simplest kind of record linkage, called *deterministic* or *rules-based record linkage*, generates links based on the number of individual identifiers that match among the available data sets.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Two records are said to match via a deterministic record linkage procedure if all or some identifiers (above a certain threshold) are identical.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Deterministic record linkage is a good option when the entities in the data sets are identified by a common identifier, or when there are several representative identifiers (e.g., name, date of birth, and sex when identifying a person) whose quality of data is relatively high.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] As an example, consider two standardized data sets, Set A and Set B, that contain different bits of information about patients in a hospital system.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] The two data sets identify patients using a variety of identifiers: Social Security Number (SSN), name, date of birth (DOB), sex, and ZIP code (ZIP).
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] The most simple deterministic record linkage strategy would be to pick a single identifier that is assumed to be uniquely identifying, say SSN, and declare that records sharing the same value identify the same person while records not sharing the same value identify different people.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] In this example, deterministic linkage based on SSN would create entities based on A1 and A2; A3 and B1; and A4.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] While A1, A2, and B2 appear to represent the same entity, B2 would not be included in the match because it is missing a value for SSN.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Handling exceptions such as missing identifiers involves the creation of additional record linkage rules.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] One such rule in the case of a missing SSN might be to compare name, date of birth, sex, and ZIP code with other records in hopes of finding a match.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] In the above example, this rule would still not match A1/A2 with B2 because the names are still slightly different: standardization put the names into the proper (Surname, Given name) format but could not discern "Bill" as a nickname for "William".
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Running names through a phonetic algorithm such as Soundex, NYSIIS, or metaphone can help to resolve these types of problems.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] However, they may still stumble over surname changes as a result of marriage or divorce, but then B2 would be matched only with A1 since the ZIP code in A2 is different.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Thus, another rule would need to be created to determine whether differences in particular identifiers are acceptable (such as ZIP code) and which are not (such as date of birth).
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] As this example demonstrates, even a small decrease in data quality or a small increase in the complexity of the data can result in a very large increase in the number of rules necessary to link records properly.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Eventually, these linkage rules will become too numerous and interrelated to build without the aid of specialized software tools.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] In addition, linkage rules are often specific to the nature of the data sets they are designed to link together.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Thus, continuous maintenance testing of these rules is necessary to ensure they continue to function as expected as new data enter the system and need to be linked.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] New data that exhibit different characteristics than were initially expected could require a complete rebuilding of the record linkage rule set, which could be a very time-consuming and expensive endeavor.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Many probabilistic record linkage algorithms assign match/non-match weights to identifiers by means of two probabilities called u and m .
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] The u probability is the probability that an identifier in two *non-matching* records will agree purely by chance.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] For example, the u probability for birth month (where twelve values are approximately uniformly distributed) is $1/12\approx 0.083$ ; identifiers with values that are not uniformly distributed will have different u probabilities for different values (possibly including missing values).
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] The m probability is the probability that an identifier in *matching* pairs will agree (or be sufficiently similar, such as strings with low Jaro-Winkler or Levenshtein distance).
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] This value would be $1.0$ in the case of perfect data, but given that this is rarely (if ever) true, it can instead be estimated.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] This estimation may be done based on prior knowledge of the data sets, by manually identifying a large number of matching and non-matching pairs to "train" the probabilistic record linkage algorithm, or by iteratively running the algorithm to obtain closer estimations of the m probability.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] The same calculations would be done for all other identifiers under consideration to find their match/non-match weights.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] The resulting total weight is then compared to the aforementioned thresholds to determine whether the pair should be linked, non-linked, or set aside for special consideration (e.g. manual validation).
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Various manual and automated methods are available to predict the best thresholds, and some record linkage software packages have built-in tools to help the user find the most acceptable values.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Because this can be a very computationally demanding task, particularly for large data sets, a technique known as *blocking* is often used to improve efficiency.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Blocking attempts to restrict comparisons to just those records for which one or more particularly discriminating identifiers agree, which has the effect of increasing the positive predictive value (precision) at the expense of sensitivity (recall).
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Thus, robust record linkage systems often use multiple blocking passes to group data in various ways in order to come up with groups of records that should be compared to each other.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] In recent years, a variety of machine learning techniques have been used in record linkage.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Higher accuracy can often be achieved by using various other machine learning techniques, including a single-layer perceptron, random forest, and SVM.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] In conjunction with distributed technologies, accuracy and scale for record linkage can be improved further.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] High quality record linkage often requires a human–machine hybrid system to safely manage uncertainty in the ever changing streams of chaotic big data.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Recognizing that linkage errors propagate into the linked data and its analysis, interactive record linkage systems have been proposed.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Interactive record linkage is defined as people iteratively fine-tuning the results from the automated methods and managing the uncertainty and its propagation to subsequent analyses.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] The main objectives of interactive record linkage systems is to manually resolve uncertain linkages and validate the results until it is at acceptable levels for the given application.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Variations of interactive record linkage that enhance privacy during the human interaction steps have also been proposed.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Record linkage is increasingly required across databases held by different organisations, where the complementary data held by these organisations can, for example, help to identify patients who are susceptible to certain adverse drug reactions (linking hospital, doctor, and pharmacy databases).
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] In many such applications, however, the databases to be linked contain sensitive information about people which cannot be shared between the organisations.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Privacy-preserving record linkage (PPRL) methods have been developed to link databases without the need to share the original sensitive values between the organisations that participate in a linkage.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] In PPRL, generally the attribute values of records to be compared are encoded or encrypted in some form.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] A popular such encoding technique used are Bloom filter, which allows approximate similarities to be calculated between encoded values without the need for sharing the corresponding sensitive plain-text values.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] At the end of the PPRL process only limited information about the record pairs classified as matches is revealed to the organisations that participate in the linkage process.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] The techniques used in PPRL must guarantee that no participating organisation, nor any external adversary, can compromise the privacy of the entities that are represented by records in the databases being linked.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] In an application with two files, A and B, denote the rows (*records*) by $\alpha (a)$ in file A and $\beta (b)$ in file B.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Assign K *characteristics* to each record.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] where K is a subscript for the characteristics (sex, age, marital status, etc.) in the files.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Most Master data management (MDM) products use a record linkage process to identify records from different sources representing the same real-world entity.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] This linkage is used to create a "golden master record" containing the cleaned, reconciled data about the entity.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] The techniques used in MDM are the same as for record linkage generally.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] MDM expands this matching not only to create a "golden master record" but also to infer relationships.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] (i.e. a person has the same/similar surname and same/similar address, this might imply they share a household relationship).
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Record linkage plays a key role in data warehousing and business intelligence.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Data warehouses serve to combine data from many different operational source systems into one logical data model, which can then be subsequently fed into a business intelligence system for reporting and analytics.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Data standardization and subsequent record linkage often occur in the "transform" portion of the extract, transform, load (ETL) process.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Record linkage is important to social history research since most data sets, such as census records and parish registers were recorded long before the invention of National identification numbers.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] When old sources are digitized, linking of data sets is a prerequisite for longitudinal study.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] This process is often further complicated by a lack of standard spelling of names, family names that change according to place of dwelling, changing of administrative boundaries, and problems of checking the data against other sources.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Record linkage was among the most prominent themes in the History and computing field in the 1980s, but has since been subject to less attention in research.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Record linkage is an important tool in creating data required for examining the health of the public and of the health care system itself.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] It can be used to improve data holdings, data collection, quality assessment, and the dissemination of information.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Data sources can be examined to eliminate duplicate records, to identify under-reporting and missing cases (e.g., census population counts), to create person-oriented health statistics, and to generate disease registries and health surveillance systems.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Some cancer registries link various data sources (e.g., hospital admissions, pathology and clinical reports, and death registrations) to generate their registries.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Record linkage is also used to create health indicators.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] For example, fetal and infant mortality is a general indicator of a country's socioeconomic development, public health, and maternal and child services.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] If infant death records are matched to birth records, it is possible to use birth variables, such as birth weight and gestational age, along with mortality data, such as cause of death, in analyzing the data.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Linkages can help in follow-up studies of cohorts or other groups to determine factors such as vital status, residential status, or health outcomes.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] Tracing is often needed for follow-up of industrial cohorts, clinical trials, and longitudinal surveys to obtain the cause of death and/or cancer.
[src:k-anonymity/record-linkage] An example of a successful and long-standing record linkage system allowing for population-based medical research is the Rochester Epidemiology Project based in Rochester, Minnesota.
[src:k-anonymity/t-closeness] Given the existence of data breaches where sensitive attributes may be inferred based upon the distribution of values for *l*-diverse data, the *t*-closeness method was created to further *l*-diversity by additionally maintaining the distribution of sensitive fields.
[src:k-anonymity/t-closeness] Yu further state in their book on privacy-preserving data mining that with this definition, threshold *t* gives an upper bound on the difference between the distribution of the sensitive attribute values within an anonymized group as compared to the global distribution of values.
[src:k-anonymity/t-closeness] They also state that for numeric attributes, using *t*-closeness anonymization is more effective than many other privacy-preserving data mining methods.
[src:k-anonymity/t-closeness] In real data sets attribute values may be skewed or semantically similar.
[src:k-anonymity/t-closeness] However, accounting for value distributions may cause difficulty in creating feasible *l*-diverse representations.
[src:k-anonymity/t-closeness] The *l*-diversity technique is useful in that it may hinder an attacker leveraging the global distribution of an attribute's data values in order to infer information about sensitive data values.
[src:k-anonymity/t-closeness] Not every value may exhibit equal sensitivity, for example, a rare positive indicator for a disease may provide more information than a common negative indicator.
[src:k-anonymity/t-closeness] Because of examples like this, *l*-diversity may be difficult and unnecessary to achieve when protecting against attribute disclosure.
